│ THOUGHT                                                                                                                                                                                  │
│ The previous fix was correct for the `fabs` intrinsic but incomplete. The `submit-patch` command revealed a similar miscompilation with the `copysign` intrinsic. The root cause is the  │
│ same: an optimization, `matchIsFiniteTest`, incorrectly assumes that sign-modifying operations like `fabs` and `copysign` do not have side effects that are guarded by the `fcmp ord`    │
│ part of the pattern.                                                                                                                                                                     │
│                                                                                                                                                                                          │
│ Specifically, `fabs` with the `nnan` attribute can turn a signaling NaN into `poison`. Similarly, `copysign(x, y)` can propagate `poison` from `y`. The original `select(fcmp ord %x,    │
│ ...)` structure prevents these poison values from being returned, but the optimized `fcmp` propagates them.                                                                              │
│                                                                                                                                                                                          │
│ The fix is to make the check in `matchIsFiniteTest` more general. Instead of only checking for `fabs` with `nnan`, I will check if the operand of the `fcmp u* %op, inf` is exactly the  │
│ same as the operand of the `fcmp ord %op, 0`. If they are not the same, it means a sign-modifying operation is present, and this optimization is unsafe because that operation might     │
│ have the side effects described above.                                                                                                                                                   │
│                                                                                                                                                                                          │
│ The check `stripSignOnlyFPOps(LHS0) == stripSignOnlyFPOps(RHS0)` is too lenient. I will replace it with a strict equality check `LHS0 == RHS0`. This ensures that we only perform the    │
│ optimization when the values being compared are identical, which is the safe subset of cases for this transformation.                                                                    │
│                                                                                                                                                                                          │
│ I will modify `llvm/lib/Transforms/InstCombine/InstCombineAndOrXor.cpp` to implement this stricter check.                                                                                │
│                                                                                                                                                                                          │
│ ```bash                                                                                                                                                                                  │
│ sed -i 's/stripSignOnlyFPOps(LHS0) == stripSignOnlyFPOps(RHS0)/LHS0 == RHS0/' llvm/lib/Transforms/InstCombine/InstCombineAndOrXor.cpp                                                    │
│ ```                                                                                                                                                                                      │
